Throughout this paper, we assume that $q$, $n$, $m$ and $\mathcal{R}$ are fixed by the application. We will refer to these values as the \emph{channel parameters}.

A main assumption of the gamma channel is that the transfer matrix $\boldsymbol{A}$ is always invertible. In random linear network coding this may not be the case with high probability when the field size is small. However the field size must be sufficiently large to allow feasible linear network coding, that is to be able to deliver the input to all destinations when no errors occur. Therefore the gamma channel is an appropriate model when it is assumed the system is designed to be feasible. 

In both~\cite{Nobrega2013} and~\cite{siavoshani2011} the authors consider (different) generalisations of the MMC channel that do not necessarily have a square full rank transfer matrix. Such channels allow modelling of network coding when no erroneous packets are injected into the network, but there may be link erasures. 
