\section{Conclusion} \label{sec:conclusion}

Theorem~\ref{capacityUGR} reduces the problem of computing the gamma channel capacity to a maximisation over a set of variables of linear rather than exponential size, since the UGR distribution is determined by the distribution $\mathcal{R}_{\boldsymbol{X}}$ on a set of size $\min\{n,m\}+1$. It is possible to write down an explicit expression for this maximisation problem in terms of the channel parameters and some efficiently computable functions from matrix theory. This expression provides a means for efficiently computing the exact channel capacity, and determining an optimal input rank distribution. The details are postponed to the full paper; we sketch some key points of the proof below. 

Using the results in previous subsections, it is not hard to write an expression for the capacity as a maximisation problem in terms of the channel parameters, the function $f$ (defined in Subsection \ref{sec:matrices}) and $h_r$ (see Definition~\ref{def:hr}). 
 Recall that $h_r$ is defined as the entropy of the output of the gamma channel when the input distribution takes a fixed rank $r$ matrix $M$ with probability 1, so we need to analyse the channel output in this case. It is simple to show that all output matrices $Y$ with a given row space $U$ occur equally often in the output; this leads to a simple formula for the entropy of $\boldsymbol{Y}$ given that ${\operatorname{Row}}(\boldsymbol{Y})=U$. So it remains to analyse the entropy of ${\operatorname{Row}}(\boldsymbol{Y})=\boldsymbol{U}$. It turns out that the probability of a given row space $U$ occurring is influenced by its dimension $u$, the dimension $h$ of its intersection with ${\operatorname{Row}}(M)$ and the channel parameters. This leads to a (fairly complicated, but explicit and easily computable) formula for the entropy of ${\operatorname{Row}}(\boldsymbol{Y})$. This leads to an expression for the capacity of the gamma channel as a maximisation problem in $\mathcal{R}_{\boldsymbol{X}}$, depending only on the channel parameters and some explicit functions from matrix theory. 

